<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. OPEN NOTES; TWENTY-ONE YEARS LATER, OAKMONT GETS REVENGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOMAS BONK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On his way to an 81, Johnny Miller shot a 43 on the front nine, including a 
start of double bogey, par, double bogey, bogey, bogey. 
</P>
<P>
 That's a long way from the final-round 63 that Miller produced to win the 1973 
U.S. Open at Oakmont. 
</P>
<P>
 For the record, Miller reached 63 Thursday with his tee shot on the 14th hole, 
which he bogeyed. 
</P>
<P>
 Miller refused to come to the interview room afterward, but had a brief 
comment for pool reporters. 
</P>
<P>
 "The (U.S. Golf Assn.) is loving it," he said. "No one is creaming the 
course." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Chris Patton, who got into the tournament as an alternate, got out of it after 
eight holes because of heat exhaustion. 
</P>
<P>
 "I felt dizzy and sick at my stomach," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Patton, he has been on a diet and lost about 40 pounds. He said 
he weighed 352 at Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
 Patton said he has been spurred to lose weight after reading a story about him 
titled, "A Giant Disappointment." 
</P>
<P>
 Patton added: "That really hurt. I've wanted to prove that even if I can't 
play golf, I can do something. I've wanted to make him eat his words." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Worst score of the day? It went to Gil Morgan, who shot a quadruple-bogey nine 
on No. 4. Tim Simpson and Ian Woosnam shot eights on the same hole. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Olin Browne, 25, of Jupiter, Fla., playing in his first U.S. Open, shot a 33 
on his front nine but finished with a 74. 
</P>
<P>
 Along the way, Browne figured out a good way to approach Oakmont. 
</P>
<P>
 "You hit the best shot you can and hold on for dear life," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
