<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAME-SEX UNIONS PRACTICED EUROPE-WIDE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 We found the Los Angeles Times' note accompanying Garry Trudeau's "Doonesbury" 
last week (which concerned John Boswell's book, "Same Sex Unions in Premodern 
Europe") to be highly misleading in implying that the same-sex union ceremony 
uncovered by Professor Boswell was primarily a phenomenon of the Eastern 
Orthodox Church. 
</P>
<P>
 In the early Christian era, there was no clear division between the Eastern 
and Roman branches of the Christian Church. Professor Boswell shows that the 
same-sex ceremony was practiced throughout Europe and, in fact, he found the 
largest number of early manuscript copies in Italy -- with no less than eight 
copies in the Vatican itself. 
</P>
<P>
 DOUG STUMPF 
</P>
<P>
 Executive Editor 
</P>
<P>
 Villard Books 
</P>
<P>
 New York 
</P>
</TEXT>
