<HEADLINE>
<P>
THREE PLAYERS SIGN WITH KINGS; ROBITAILLE HAS SURGERY ON ANKLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Kings have signed free-agent forward Rob Brown, free-agent defenseman 
Michel Petit and 1992 draft choice Jeff Shevalier, General Manager Sam McMaster 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown, 26, was the most valuable player and leading scorer in the 
International Hockey League last season, getting 155 points, including 42 
goals, in 79 games for Kalamazoo.A 5-foot-11, 185-pound right wing, Brown is a 
veteran of more than five NHL seasons and has accumulated 351 points and 514 
penalty minutes in 351 games with four teams. 
</P>
<P>
 Petit, 30, is a 6-1, 210-pound veteran of 11 NHL seasons with five teams. Last 
season, he played in 63 games for the Calgary Flames, getting 23 points and 110 
penalty minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 Shevalier, 20, is a 5-11, 185-pound left wing who has enjoyed two consecutive 
100-point seasons in the Ontario Hockey League. The fifth-round draft pick 
signed a three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
 The Kings also announced that Luc Robitaille underwent surgery to repair a 
slight fracture in his right ankle on Wednesday, and is expected to be fully 
recovered in time for training camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
