<HEADLINE>
<P>
FAMILIAR FOES MAY MEET AGAIN IN SUMMER; BASKETBALL: MATER DEI AND EDISON BOYS, 
WOODBRIDGE AND MATER DEI GIRLS MIGHT FACE OFF. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB ROHWER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Mater Dei boys' basketball team, led by Schea Cotton, a 6-foot-5 sophomore 
who was a member of The Times' All-Orange County basketball team last season, 
will compete in six tournaments this summer. 
</P>
<P>
 The Monarchs, 33-1 last season in winning their third consecutive Southern 
Section title, play host to their tournament beginning June 22. They'll also 
take part in the Surf City tournament July 1-3, the Nike-Mater Dei tournament 
July 6-10, the Great Western Shoot-Out July 11-15, the Las Vegas Nike 
Invitational July 16-22 and the BCI Tournament in Phoenix July 25-29. 
</P>
<P>
 Cotton will be joined by returning seniors Clay McKnight at guard and Shaun 
Jackson at forward. McKnight is the son of of the Monarchs' coach, Gary 
McKnight, who has a career record of 352-29 at the school. 
</P>
<P>
 Junior Olujimi Mann and Santa Ana Valley will participate in the El Dorado and 
Cypress tournaments as well as the Mater Dei, Surf City and Nike-Mater Dei 
tournaments, where Mann could go face-to-face with his former Monarch 
teammates. 
</P>
<P>
 Mann, who transferred after his freshman season at Mater Dei, was The Times' 
all-county first-team selection. He helped the Falcons (26-4) reach the 
Southern Section Division I-AA semifinals last season. 
</P>
<P>
 Edison (19-11), which gave Mater Dei a scare in the Southern Section I-A final 
before losing, 65-59, could get another crack at the Monarchs in the Surf City 
tournament. The Chargers, a senior-dominated squad last season, are also 
scheduled to play in the University tournament July 15-17. 
</P>
<P>
 Pacifica (30-2), which won the section III-A title and reached the State 
Division III final last season, appears to be in for a rebuilding year after 
losing the bulk of its players to graduation. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mariners, who will be led by guard Jaimi Bessho and forward Ed MacDonald, 
will get opportunities to regroup this summer in seven tournaments, beginning 
with Mater Dei's. 
</P>
<P>
 The Brea-Olinda girls' team, four-time defending State champions and the 
nation's No. 1-ranked squad last season, plays host to a tournament beginning 
today. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ladycats (33-0) lost to graduation their top three players -- Nicole 
Erickson, The Times' county player of the year; Colleen Hudson and Sarah 
Beckley -- and saw their coach, walk-on John Hattrup, quit May 31 after one 
season on the job. 
</P>
<P>
 But guard Kiyoko Miller and forward Lee Moulin lead a talented group of 
players for new coach Jeff Sink, the third-winningest girls' coach in Alaska 
history at Fairbanks Lathrop, where his teams won state titles in 1990 and 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
 The Woodbridge girls' team (32-1), which won the section II-AA title and 
reached the State Division II championship game, will be without its floor 
leader, Jamie Oenning (UCLA), but she is all the young Warriors lose. 
</P>
<P>
 They'll participate in the Estancia and Marina tournaments, where they could 
meet Melody Peterson and the Mater Dei Monarchs (24-5), who gained the section 
Division I-A final. 
</P>
